# Table Component Rules

## Overview
All tables must use TanStack Table via the `AppDataTable` wrapper component from `@/components/DataTable`. Column definitions must be defined at module scope, never inside a component's render function.

## Rules

### 1. Use `AppDataTable` Only
Use the `AppDataTable` component for all table rendering. Never import or use `useReactTable`, `flexRender`, `getCoreRowModel`, or raw TanStack Table components (`<Table>`, `<TableHeader>`, `<TableBody>`, `<TableRow>`, `<TableCell>`) directly. Those are internal to `AppDataTable`.

### 2. Column Definitions in Outer Scope
Column definitions must be defined outside the component scope as module-level `const` or a `createColumns()` factory function. Never define `ColumnDef<T>[]` inside a component render.

- **Simple tables** (no callbacks): export a `const columns: ColumnDef<T>[]` at module scope
- **Tables with actions**: use a `createColumns()` factory function exported from a dedicated `columns.ts` file

### 3. Hidable Columns
Tables must support column visibility toggling. `AppDataTable` provides a built-in "Columns" dropdown. Ensure every column has an explicit `id` property so it appears in the visibility menu.

### 4. Empty State
`AppDataTable` handles empty state implicitly via the `emptyState` prop which accepts `<EmptyStateContent>{...}</EmptyStateContent>`. When omitted, a default "No results" placeholder is shown. Callers must not add their own empty-state conditionals or inline "No results." text.

## Code Snippets

### Column Definitions at Module Scope

```typescript
import type { ColumnDef } from "@tanstack/react-table";

type MyRow = {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  email: string | null;
};

const columns: ColumnDef<MyRow>[] = [
  { id: "sn", header: "S/N", cell: ({ row }) => row.index + 1 },
  { id: "name", header: "Name", accessorKey: "name" },
  { id: "email", header: "Email", accessorKey: "email" },
];
```

### createColumns Factory (with callbacks)

```typescript
// columns.ts
export function createColumns(actions: {
  onView: (id: string) => void;
}): ColumnDef<MyRow>[] {
  return [
    {
      id: "name",
      header: "Name",
      accessorKey: "name",
      cell: ({ row }) => (
        <button onClick={() => actions.onView(row.original.id)}>
          {row.getValue("name")}
        </button>
      ),
    },
    { id: "email", header: "Email", accessorKey: "email" },
  ];
}
```

### Usage with AppDataTable

```typescript
const cols = React.useMemo(() => createColumns({ onView: handleView }), []);

return (
  <AppDataTable
    columns={cols}
    data={rows}
    onRowClick={(row) => handleSelect(row.id)}
    emptyState={
      <EmptyStateContent>
        <EmptyStateTitle>No items found</EmptyStateTitle>
        <EmptyStateDescription>Try adjusting your filters.</EmptyStateDescription>
      </EmptyStateContent>
    }
  />
);
```

### Column Visibility Dropdown (built into AppDataTable)

```typescript
// DataTable.tsx — no action needed from callers
<DropdownMenu>
  <DropdownMenuTrigger asChild>
    <Button variant="outline" className="ml-auto">
      Columns <ChevronDown />
    </Button>
  </DropdownMenuTrigger>
  <DropdownMenuContent align="end">
    {table
      .getAllColumns()
      .filter((column) => column.getCanHide())
      .map((column) => (
        <DropdownMenuCheckboxItem
          key={column.id}
          className="capitalize"
          checked={column.getIsVisible()}
          onCheckedChange={(value) => column.toggleVisibility(!!value)}
        >
          {column.id}
        </DropdownMenuCheckboxItem>
      ))}
  </DropdownMenuContent>
</DropdownMenu>
```

## Bad Examples

```typescript
// ❌ Raw TanStack table setup inside component
const table = useReactTable({ data, columns, getCoreRowModel: getCoreRowModel() });
return (
  <Table>
    <TableHeader>...</TableHeader>
    <TableBody>{flexRender(...)}</TableBody>
  </Table>
);

// ❌ Column definitions inside component render
function MyTable() {
  const columns: ColumnDef<Row>[] = [...]; // wrong scope
  return <AppDataTable columns={columns} ... />;
}

// ❌ Caller handling empty state inline
{data.length === 0 && <p>No results</p>} // AppDataTable handles this
```
